{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011L5bXvxurxPgitpos9u88f","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's a shell quoting issue. The single quotes in the node -e script are conflicting with the bash single quote delimiters. I need to escape them. Let me use a different approach.\n\nActually, let me just use a Python script to write the full Node.js file. The Python heredoc (`<< 'PYEOF'`) was getting interrupted, but a `python -c \"...\"` might work if I can handle the escaping properly.\n\nWait - the `python -c \"...\"` would need all the double quotes escaped since the outer delimiter is double quotes. That's also problematic.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach: write the classification data as a JSON file using node, then have a simple node script read it and combine it with vendor data.\n\n\nI'm thinking I should split this into two separate node commands - one to write out the classification data as JSON, and another to read both files and merge them together. The challenge is that the classification object is large, so I might need to build it incrementally by writing the file header, appending the data in chunks, then adding the footer. But the quoting complexities keep getting in the way, so maybe Python would be cleaner here.\n\nActually, I'm realizing Python's file I/O with `open()` would handle the special characters and escaping much better than trying to work around shell quoting issues. I could write the entire Node.js script using Python's multi-line strings passed through `python -c`, since double quotes are the outer delimiter and I only need to escape those - single quotes in JavaScript are fine. The heredoc approach kept failing with exit code 126, so let me try this Python approach instead. I'm realizing the encoding issue is more complex than I thought—Python's openpyxl represents the corrupted vendor names with replacement characters, which is different from ho